Kowloon's Jade Magistracy classifies Warlocks under Indigo jurisdiction — anomalous spiritual phenomena — with specific provisions for the compact structure. Standard Indigo filing requires description of the spiritual phenomenon source; Warlock compact filing instead requires description of the practitioner's compact terms and price structure, treating the entity as the practitioner's operational context rather than as a regulated phenomenon. The Covenant Crisis Prevention framework's concern with Warlocks is the compact price's attention-cost dimension: an entity accumulating knowledge of a practitioner's situation during crisis events becomes an information-security risk if that entity is also accumulating knowledge of Kowloon's crisis response operations. Registered Warlocks in Kowloon are required to maintain an operational log allowing the Magistracy to assess what information was available during each hex application — designed to detect the entity-attention problem rather than address it directly.

