Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant framework is specifically important for Warlock practitioners: the compact structure creates information accumulation risks that sealed warrants would make impossible to assess: a Warlock compelled to serve under a covert commission agreement exposes their compact entity's accumulated knowledge to the commissioning party's operational context. Kiess protections prevent this compulsion regardless of the practitioner's capabilities. Wall Command's primary interest is ward-disruption: frontier fortifications compromised by spiritual anomaly require clearance operations that Warlock hex craft can facilitate in ways Paladin advance-and-sanctify doctrine cannot. The frontier context creates demand for binding hex applications — temporary mobility constraints during breach situations where Guard capacity is insufficient for physical containment. Kiess assesses Warlocks by operational effectiveness without engaging compact entity nature questions that preoccupy other cities.

