Mafdet's Harbor Ledger House handles Warlock registration under a compact documentation framework that treats the shadow compact as a form of commercial partnership agreement. The oath obligation requires Warlocks to attest that their compact terms do not create obligations to their compact entity that would conflict with their obligations to clients or to the city's commercial framework. The Swift Court has addressed at least one case in which a Warlock's entity appeared to have directed hex applications against a party with whom the Warlock had no engagement contract, raising whether the practitioner or the entity was the responsible party for an unauthorized operation. The court's ruling was inconclusive — it declined to assign entity legal standing — but the filing framework was subsequently updated to require Warlocks to attest that they maintain operational direction over their compact applications rather than responding to entity direction.

